<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="c7fd488171dcc9f20d438c7ec38b96d2" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> LOTR Q&A Rulings from 11/27/03<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.86)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=617'>Enrique "Max of Tat" Huerta</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=617&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> December 11, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Not for review<br />
Originally posted on 11/27/03<br />
==============================<br />
<br />
<br />
Hello All!!<br />
<br />
   First off, HAPPY THANKSGIVING to all of you! I know not everyone on DeckTech is from the United States, but I still think wishing everyone and their families a very joyous 4th Thursday of November is a good thing. (=<br />
<br />
   This is also the last weekend to sumbit a deck for the DeckTech Star Trek 2E contest I&#39;m helping run. A box of Call to Arms goes to the winner! For more information, go http://www.decktech.net/index.php?artc=381. It&#39;s not too late to enter, but if you wait much longer, it will be.<br />
<br />
   Well, Return of the King has released. Many new things (initiative and threats) have been added to the game. As such, it&#39;s no surprise that there are also many new rules questions that have come up recently. And of course there are always rules questions from past cards too. (=<br />
<br />
   During the last update there appears to have been some confusion regarding my ruling with Saruman, Servant of the Eye and Defender +1 companions. As a reminder, I told you that you cannot use Saruman (or any <Assignment:</b> action) to assign more than 1 minion to a companion, even a defender +X. It seemed that my word choice was either not clear, or did not resemble a previous ruling, therefore some players (yes, more than 1) were confused. So I will try to explain it again, and hopefully I get it right this time (again). (=<br />
<br />
The assignment phase has 3 parts:<br />
  1. assignment actions<br />
  2. assign defenders<br />
  3. assign leftover minions<br />
<br />
1. Assignment actions include the game text of cards such as Saruman, Servant of the Eye, Vision from Afar, Southron Commander, Lindenroot, Orc Assassin, and Smeagol, Always Helps. Normally assignment actions create an assignment two characters. These assignments must result in one-on-one skirmishes, and the characters involved must previously be unassigned. This is regardless of whether or not the companion or ally is a defender +X. (NOTE: This is also the time in which you HAVE to use Unhasty Ents&#39; assignment action game text in order to allow them to participate in skirmishes.)<br />
<br />
2. After both players have passed their skirmish actions, we proceed to the assign defenders part of the phase. The Free People&#39;s Player may not assign their companions (and participating allies) to one-on-one skirmishes with participating minions. Again, at this time all skirmishes are one-on-one with the exception of defender +X. A defender +X is allowed to be assigned to +X additional minions. The defender will skirmish only once, and it will be against all the minions at once.<br />
<br />
3. After the FPP has assigned all of the defenders, the Shadow player may assign any participating, still unassigned minions to any companion or participating ally. These skirmishes do NOT have to be one-on-one, or involve previously unassigned companions or allies. After all parts the assignment phase has completed and all responses to assignments have resolved, the players proceed to the skirmish phase(s).<br />
<br />
   Again, have a Happy Thanksgiving everyone and I&#39;ll see you again in two weeks!<br />
<br />
- Enrique<br />
<br />
<br />
<h3>Questions about Card Rulings:</h3><br />
<b>with terrible and evil, can you exert gandalf zero times to wound a nazgul zero times, and then wound it again, resulting in one wound? [the Mad Maia]</b><br />
<br />
Assuming that Gandalf is active and in play, yes you can choose to exert him 0 times and still get a bonus 1 wound against a Nazgul. I would also probably argue that even through you&#39;re exerting 0 times, you can not play this card if Gandalf is either not in play and active or if Gandalf is exhausted.<br />
<br />
<b>Hi Enrique, <br />
<br />
I have some questions about response actions. <br />
<br />
1.Can i play 2 or more responses to the same action. (ex. Play 2 not listenig and one dont follow the lights when smeagol wins a skirmish) <br />
<br />
2.Can i play Not listening if smeagol in not wounded but frodo have burdens, and remove the 2 burdens?? [Kenny]</b><br />
<br />
1. Yes, you make respond to the same trigger more than once. Assuming that each response is a legal one. So a Band of the Eye can remove 2 multiply times when it wins a skirmish, but the Twilight Witch-king cannot. Playing Not Listening twice and Don&#39;t Follow the Lights once as a respose to Smeagol winning a skirmish is a legal card play.<br />
<br />
2. Yes. Healing Smeagol is an effect of Not Listening. All actions are carried out to the fullest extent possible and ignore the rest. In this case you would ignore the healing and just remove the 2 burdens.<br />
<br />
<b>Hi Enrique, <br />
<br />
again I&#39;ve to consult you to get answers to this questions: <br />
<br />
1. May I use the maneuver action on Theoden/Eowyn that allows me to play a possession on him/her to heal an ally/her even if there are no wounds an allies/her? <br />
<br />
2. A couple of uruk machines is out and Gandalf tries to sleep them away. May I use the response of the machine(don&#39;t know the exact name of the card) that prevents another machine from being discarded? In my opinion the free peoples player chooses in which order the effects are discarded, so when I discard these very conditions first, there&#39;s no way it could prevent the others from being discarded. Or do I think too complicated and all effect are simply discarded without a possibility to prevent it? <br />
<br />
3. When an action on a card like Bilbo Gentlehobbit or some sauron orcs tells me to discard effect, may I also discard effects that I have in hand (that are not in play) or stacked for example on a dwarven card? <br />
<br />
I wait for your answers that will bring clarity as they always do. Thx&Greez [Dirayn] </b> <br />
<br />
1. Yes. The healing of an ally or companion is the effect of the action. You may play the possession even if there isn&#39;t a wound to heal. (NOTE: This is not the same for Hrethel. Healing the minion is the cost of Hrethel&#39;s game text, not the effect of it. If you cannot heal the minion, then you can not pay the cost of the action and you would not get the effects of the action.)<br />
<br />
2. You may use the Siege Engine to prevent any and all Machines from being discarded. Siege Engine states that &quot;if one or more of your machines are about to be discarded by an opponent, discard this condition to prevent that. Since Sleep, Caradhras is about to discard one or more of your machine, you may use 1 Siege Engine to prevent that and to protect all of your remaining machines. <br />
<br />
3. The default meaning of &quot;discard&quot; is to &quot;discard from play&quot;. So unless specified from a different location, you would have to discard a Tale (for Bilbo) or a condition (for Orc Patrol/Gate Sentry) from play, not from hand or stacked on a Dwarven condition. <br />
<br />
<b>The new site &quot;Minas Tirith First Circle&quot; forces all companions to wound if the fellowship moves in the regroup phase. But does that really work if I move from another site, and my opponent plays Úlairë Nelya, Lt. of Morgul? As you know, he replaces sites by exertion - but my opinion is that my fellowship doesn´t wound because -I did not move from THAT site- (the game text says that they wound When You Move From THIS Site). Or am I wrong?  [Stefan]</b><br />
<br />
You are correct. You would not have wound your companions because you did not move from that site. You moved from your site 6.<br />
<br />
<b>This is a simple question, that I should know the answer to, but I&#39;m not sure so I though I&#39;d check. As I understand it, I can play a skirmish: pump on a companion or minion during any skirmish phase, whether or not the character is involved in that skirmish, and whether or not they are even assigned to a skirmish. This means that I can play Severed His Bonds at T5-T9 and SaS at T6-T9 on a hobbit not assigned to a skirmish just to cycle my hand. Correct? However I cannot play these events on unassigned hobbits at earlier sites, as there is no skirmish to cancel. Right? Thanks for your patience. [Erithil]</b><br />
<br />
You actually can play them at any site T1-T9 for no effect. If the currently resolving skirmish is not involving a Hobbit, the cards would have no effect (in terms of cancelling a skirmish), but you could still play them. At higher sites (T5-T9 or T6-T9), the cards would have an effect although it&#39;s not likely those effects will come into play; maybe Swiftly and Softly vs. the Twilight Witch-king.<br />
<br />
An important thing to remember. If the current skirmish involves a Hobbit (at T1-T4 or T1-T5), you cannot play the cards targetting a different Hobbit to avoid cancelling the skirmish. Swiftly and Softly and Severed Their Bonds do not target a Hobbit, they target the skirmish involving a Hobbit. I have seen players try to use 3 stealths for a single skirmish (to clear out their hand) play it incorrectly by trying to avoid cancelling the skirmish with the first one. <br />
<br />
<b>Hi Enrique, I have a question for you regarding a card from the new ROTK-set: Loathsome (7R182,Ringwraith,skirmish-event: if a skirmish involving a nazgûl is about to end, discard a possession borne by a companion in that skirmish). Actually I have two questions: 1) When I kill the Nazgûl in the skirmish phase (say with a Power According To His Stature), my opponent can still use this cards&#39; text, right? 2) What happens when I cancel the skirmish (Scouting, Gandalf&#39;s Staff, for example)? The skirmish is still about to end, so you can still use this card? Thanks a bunch! [Niek Vanderispaillie]  </b><br />
<br />
1. Incorrect. Loathsome requires a skirmish involving a Nazgul. If the Nazgul has died, it is no longer &quot;involving a Nazgul.&quot;<br />
<br />
2. Correct. Even a cancelled skirmish is &quot;about to end&quot;. Since none of the above mentioned cards remove the Nazgul, the skirmish that is about is end still involves a Nazgul so you&#39;d be able to play Loathsome in this instance.<br />
<br />
<b>Hi! Is it possible to exert two diffrent Bounders to make a hobbit not to be overwhelmed unless his strength was tripled and tripled again....adding the two together... Thanks. [Colin]</b><br />
<br />
Incorrect. Bounder is like a switch. It either changes the overwhelming rule or it doesn&#39;t. It does not modify the rule. So if you use 1 Bounder to prevent a Hobbit from being overwhemled useless its stregth is tripled, using a second Bounder will have no effect (during the same skirmish).<br />
<br />
<h3>Questions about Game/Tournament Rulings:</h3><br />
<br />
<b>Enrique, <br />
<br />
Perhaps you have answered it in another Q&A but I didn&#39;t find it anywhere in the list so here it is. I was having an off hand discussion with one of my buddies about LOTR and we were talking about the skirmish phase. Say I have Aragorn, RotN str 10 with a ranger sword against an Uruk Rager str 9. Because I am currently winning the skirmish I pass and ask my opponent if he has an action. He plays a ferocity making his uruk str 11. I then counter by playing Swordarm of the White tower making aragorn str 12. We have no more actions between the two of us so we both pass and therefore Aragorn wins. My friend says that this is not the right way to resolve a skirmish. He says that once I pass as I did at first (asking my opponent if he has an action) I can not play any skirmish actions during the turn therefore allowing my opponent to win the skirmish with a ferocity instead of allowing me to then counter with the swordarm. I thought that the skirmish finishes only when all players pass in the same round ex: I pass then he passes. Not when I pass, he plays, he passes. Can you for once and for all settle this debate between us? [Death Dealer] </b><br />
<br />
You were correct. A skimish phase (like most other phases) only &quot;proceeds&quot; when both players consecutively pass their actions. Until both players consecutively pass their action, the phase continues and both players may still play actions. For example, a skirmish phase could look like this:<br />
<br />
FPP: Pass<br />
S: Skirmish Action #1<br />
FPP: Skirmish Action #2<br />
S: Pass<br />
FPP: Skirmish Action #3<br />
S: Skirmish Action #4<br />
FPP: Pass<br />
S: Pass<br />
<i>Proceed to the next part of the phase (determining the winner/loser).</i><br />
<br />
As you can see, both players at some point passed their actions and played an action later. It wasn&#39;t until they both consecutively passed that the skirmish proceded to the next part of the phase.<br />
<br />
<b>Enrique, I remember somewhere that it says place your frodo and one ring on the table face up and then bid? The rule book doesn&#39;t really clarify it as to if he&#39;s face up the whole time or just after bidding. You have to make sure they have a ring and frodo before you bid don&#39;t you? Otherwise, they could possibly change the frodo they want to play after bidding. Also, in Tower Block (or tower block site path)...Player A is playing Aragorn, Wingfoot with two unbound hobbits. Both of these happen at site 8 or 9. Player A moves Site 8 is Nan Curunir [Plains: Response: If your mounted minion is about to take a wound, remove two (Twilight) to prevent that wound] Player A moves site 9 is Saruman&#39;s Laboratory [Response: If your minion is about to take a wound, discard two cards from hand to prevent that wound] and wounds two minions or a minion twice with Wingfoot&#39;s text [each time the fellowship moves, you may wound a minion for each unbound hobbit you can spot] Can the shawdow player prevent these wounds? If so, at which site, and why? Thanks, [Christian ck1]</b><br />
<br />
1. You should not have to worry about a player switching out their Frodo in a tournament. It is illegal to switch Frodo. (Not that person that is willing to cheat would suddenly follow that rule.) It&#39;s just that there would be little advantage to doing so. You completely control what you bid, so it shouldn&#39;t be a surprise to you. Secondly, having them show their Frodo before you bid doesn&#39;t stop them from switching it before that time. It would be nice if players didn&#39;t cheat, but this would probably not be a place to worry about.<br />
<br />
2. A move consists of 3 parts:<br />
 - moves from<br />
 - moves<br />
 - moves to<br />
<br />
Until you resolve all of the &quot;moves from&quot;, &quot;moves&quot;, and &quot;moves to&quot; actions, the fellowship is still considerd to be at the previous site. Aragorn, Wingfoot is a &quot;moves&quot; action. So the Shadow player may use the game text of Nan Curunir (assuming there was twilight in the pool) to protect the mounted Nazgul. (NOTE: Twilight is added for the new site Shadow number and for the number of companions as a &quot;moves to&quot; action.)<br />
<br />
<br />
- Enrique<br />
